intro: Dryandra quinquedentata, commonly known as the Five-toothed Dryandra, is a species of flowering plant in the Proteaceae family. It is native to Western Australia and is characterized by its striking, urn-shaped flowers that range in color from white to pink. The plant typically grows as a shrub, reaching heights of up to 2 meters, with narrow, leathery leaves. Its flowers bloom in summer, attracting a variety of pollinators such as birds and insects. The species is known for its ecological importance in supporting local wildlife and its role in the unique flora of the region.
